{"vocabInfos":[{"lsjDefs":"<b> ἀπολογ-έομαι</b>, <br /> <i>aorist</i> ἀπελογησάμην[<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Bacchae” 41, 5th c.BC: Antipho Orator 5.13, but _falsa lectio_ in 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Sophista” 261c, 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Anabasis” 5.6.3\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; also <i>aorist</i> <i>passive</i> ἀπελογήθην[<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Antipho Orator 2.3.1, +others, 2nd c.AD: Alexander Rhetor 12 (probably suprious in 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Historia Graeca (Hellenica)” 1.4.13)\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]: <i>perfect</i> ἀπολελόγημαι[<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Andocides Orator 1.33, 5th-6th c.BC: Isocrates Orator 12.218 (in _passive_ sense, 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Respublica” 607b)\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]:—<b>speak in defence, defend oneself,</b> opposed to κατηγορεῖν, περί τινος <b>about</b> a thing, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Antipho Orator 5.7, 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 1.72\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; πρὸς τὴν μαρτυρίαν <b>in reference</b> or <b>answer to</b> the evidence, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Antipho Orator 2.4.3, compare 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 6.29; πρός τινας \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<b>before..,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Eupolis Comicus 357, compare 2nd c.BC: Polybius Historicus 22.6.4: later, with _dative_, κατηγορίαις 1st-2nd c.AD: Plutarchus Biographus et Philosophus “Themistocles” 23\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; ἀ. ὑπέρ τινος <b>speak in</b> another's <b>behalf,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 7.161, 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Bacchae” 41, 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Respublica” 488a, etc.\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; ἀ. ὑπέρ τινος <b>speak in support of</b> a fact, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Antipho Orator 3.2.1; ὑπὲρ τῆς ἀδικίας 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Gorgias” 480b\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; πρὸς Μέλητον <b>in answer to</b> him, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] “Ap.” 24b: _absolutely_, παρὼν ἀ. 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 6.136, 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Thesmophoriazusae” 188; ὁ ἀπολογούμενος \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<b>the defendant,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] “V.” 778, 5th-6th c.BC: Andocides Orator 1.6. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__2</b></Level3> with <i>accusative</i> <i>of things</i>, <b>defend oneself against,</b> ἀ. τὰς διαβολάς[<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 8.109\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; τὰς πράξεις <b>defend</b> what one has done, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th c.BC: Aeschines Orator 1.92. \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__3</b></Level3> ἀ. τι ἔς τι <b>allege in one's defence</b> against a charge, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 3.63; ἀ. πρὸς τὰ κατηγορημένα μηδέν 5th c.BC: Lysias Orator 12.38; τί ποτε ἀπολογήσεσθαι μέλλει μο; 5th c.BC: Antipho Orator 1.7 codices; ταῦτα ἀ. ὡς.. 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Phaedo” 69d; ἔργοις καλλίστοις ἀ. ὡς.. 5th c.BC: Lysias Orator 2.65; ἀ. ὅτι οὐδένα ἀδικῶ 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Oeconomicus” 11.22; ἀ. ἀπολογίαν 2nd c.AD: Lucianus Sophista “Hes.” 6. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__4</b></Level3> ἀ. δίκην θανάτου <b>speak against</b> sentence of death <b>passing on one,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 8.68.\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>] —Prose word, used once in Trag., see above—The _preposition_ ἀπό implies the <b>remoual</b> of a charge.","strongNumber":"G0626","accentedUnicode":"ἀπολογέομαι","relatedNos":[{"strongNumber":"G0379","matchingForm":"ἀναπολόγητος","stepTransliteration":"anapologētos","gloss":"inexcusable","_zh_tw_Gloss":"無可推諉","_es_Gloss":"inexcusable","_zh_Gloss":"无可推诿"},{"strongNumber":"G0575","matchingForm":"ἀπό","stepTran